  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti. How was your morning?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "It was okay. I studied a bit for NEET PG. My head is full of anatomy and pharmacology. Sometimes I feel like I am going to crack. But today I feel hopeful. I think I got a bit better at some topics."
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Studying anatomy and pharmacology is no joke. Filling your head with that much info feels like a mountain to climb. I get that — especially when it all starts to blend. What topic gave you that hopeful boost today?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Oh, you know, I worked on cardiovascular pharmacology. It's so confusing, but today I finally got the difference between beta-blockers and calcium channel blockers. Aajcha din thoda achha lagala. Maybe I can remember this!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"I get how confusing it can be — those drug names are tricky! Aajcha din thoda achha lagala — that’s a good feeling to hold on to. What made it click for you today?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I made a small table comparing beta-blockers and CCBs — like action, uses, side effects. Visualizing it helped a lot. I even explained it to myself out loud, like a teacher. That made me confident I actually understood it. Maybe I should do this for other topics too. What do you think?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Turning complex topics into simple tables is a smart move — it makes the big picture easier to hold. Explaining it out loud is like testing yourself, and that builds real confidence. What’s one other topic you’ll try this with next?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I think I’ll try this with diuretics next. Thiazides, loop diuretics, potassium-sparing — they all mix in my mind. Maybe a table will sort them out. But honestly, I’m a bit scared to start. It’s like climbing a mountain again."
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Sorting out diuretics can feel like untangling a knot, but your mountain-climbing mindset is already halfway there. Take one step — sketch a small table, even for just one type. How do you want to start?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Maybe start with loop diuretics. They seem the most important for exams. I’ll list their mechanism, uses, and side effects. If that works, I can add the others. Thanks, Maya. I should get back to it. Talk to you later."
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Loop diuretics are a solid place to start — they’re a big piece of the puzzle. Your plan sounds clear, and I’m sure it’ll help untangle the rest. Take your time, and tell me how it goes later. Talk soon!\""
    }
  ],
